<paragraph blockId="37.[345,505,1619,1643]" box="[345,505,1619,1643]" pageId="37" pageNumber="190">
<figureCitation box="[345,505,1619,1643]" captionStart="Text-fig" captionStartId="39.[125,206,1690,1711]" captionTargetBox="[125,1440,151,1669]" captionTargetId="figure-112@39.[123,795,148,1197]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="Text-fig. 24. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images (a, c, d) and synchrotron radiation X-ray tomographic microscopy (SRXTM) images (b, e) of fruits and seeds of Serialis antiqua (a, b) and Serialis parva (c–e); Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a, b) Serialis antiqua lateral view of fruit showing smooth partly abraded fruit wall (a) and longitudinal section (b, SRXTM orthoslice yz0862) showing six closely adhering seeds, some of which are mature with well-preserved nutritive tissue; c–e) Serialis parva lateral view of fruit showing faint ribs (c), finely pitted seed surface with undulate anticlinal walls of the exotestal cells (d), and transverse section showing two closely adhering seeds (SRXTM orthoslice xy0913, e). Specimens, TV43-S174480 (a, b), TV43-S170076 (c), TV43-S170079 (d), TV43-S174477 (e). Scale bars 300 Μm (a–c, e), 50 Μm (d)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386285" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386285/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="190">Text-fig. 24c–e</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="190" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="37.[106,745,1667,1921]" pageId="37" pageNumber="190">
D e s c r i p t i o n a n d r e m a r k s. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="E. M. FRIIS, P. R. CRANE et K. R. PEDERSEN" authorityYear="2019" box="[581,744,1667,1691]" class="Lycopodiopsida" family="Selaginellaceae" genus="Serialis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Selaginellales" pageId="37" pageNumber="190" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis box="[581,744,1667,1691]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="190">Serialis parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar to 
<emphasis box="[328,506,1700,1724]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="190">Serialis antiqua</emphasis>
in organization and seed coat structure, but the fruits are smaller and there are only one or two seeds per fruit (
<figureCitation box="[459,628,1765,1789]" captionStart="Text-fig" captionStartId="39.[125,206,1690,1711]" captionTargetBox="[125,1440,151,1669]" captionTargetId="figure-112@39.[123,795,148,1197]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="Text-fig. 24. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images (a, c, d) and synchrotron radiation X-ray tomographic microscopy (SRXTM) images (b, e) of fruits and seeds of Serialis antiqua (a, b) and Serialis parva (c–e); Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a, b) Serialis antiqua lateral view of fruit showing smooth partly abraded fruit wall (a) and longitudinal section (b, SRXTM orthoslice yz0862) showing six closely adhering seeds, some of which are mature with well-preserved nutritive tissue; c–e) Serialis parva lateral view of fruit showing faint ribs (c), finely pitted seed surface with undulate anticlinal walls of the exotestal cells (d), and transverse section showing two closely adhering seeds (SRXTM orthoslice xy0913, e). Specimens, TV43-S174480 (a, b), TV43-S170076 (c), TV43-S170079 (d), TV43-S174477 (e). Scale bars 300 Μm (a–c, e), 50 Μm (d)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386285" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386285/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="190">Text-fig. 24c–e</figureCitation>
). The seed coat is mesotestal-endotestal with surface of mesotesta characterized by a jigsaw puzzle shaped pattern from the strongly undulate anticlinal walls of the mesotestal cells (
<figureCitation box="[113,257,1897,1921]" captionStart="Text-fig" captionStartId="39.[125,206,1690,1711]" captionTargetBox="[125,1440,151,1669]" captionTargetId="figure-112@39.[123,795,148,1197]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="Text-fig. 24. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images (a, c, d) and synchrotron radiation X-ray tomographic microscopy (SRXTM) images (b, e) of fruits and seeds of Serialis antiqua (a, b) and Serialis parva (c–e); Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a, b) Serialis antiqua lateral view of fruit showing smooth partly abraded fruit wall (a) and longitudinal section (b, SRXTM orthoslice yz0862) showing six closely adhering seeds, some of which are mature with well-preserved nutritive tissue; c–e) Serialis parva lateral view of fruit showing faint ribs (c), finely pitted seed surface with undulate anticlinal walls of the exotestal cells (d), and transverse section showing two closely adhering seeds (SRXTM orthoslice xy0913, e). Specimens, TV43-S174480 (a, b), TV43-S170076 (c), TV43-S170079 (d), TV43-S174477 (e). Scale bars 300 Μm (a–c, e), 50 Μm (d)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386285" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386285/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="190">Text-fig. 24d</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[106,744,1944,2100]" lastBlockId="37.[820,1459,1258,1315]" pageId="37" pageNumber="190">
A f f i n i t y a n d o t h e r o c c u r r e n c e s. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="E. M. FRIIS, P. R. CRANE et K. R. PEDERSEN" authorityYear="2019" class="Lycopodiopsida" family="Selaginellaceae" genus="Serialis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Selaginellales" pageId="37" pageNumber="190" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="190">Serialis parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is common in the Torres Vedras mesofossil flora. It also occurs at the Buarcos locality where it is rare (
<bibRefCitation author="Friis, E. M. &amp; Crane, P. R. &amp; Pedersen, K. R." pageId="37" pageNumber="190" pagination="93 - 127" refId="ref75830" refString="Friis, E. M., Crane, P. R., Pedersen, K. R. (2019 a): Extinct diversity among Early Cretaceous angiosperms: meso- fossil evidence of early Magnoliales from Portugal. - International Journal of Plant Sciences, 180: 93 - 127. https: // doi. org / 10.1086 / 701319" type="journal article" year="2019">Friis et al. 2019a</bibRefCitation>
). Like other species of 
<emphasis box="[456,537,2043,2067]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="190">Serialis</emphasis>
, the relationship of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="E. M. FRIIS, P. R. CRANE et K. R. PEDERSEN" authorityYear="2019" box="[106,195,2076,2099]" class="Lycopodiopsida" family="Selaginellaceae" genus="Serialis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Selaginellales" pageId="37" pageNumber="190" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis box="[106,195,2076,2099]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="190">S. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="JUSS. ex BERCHT. et J. PRESL" authorityYear="1820" box="[281,416,2076,2100]" class="Magnoliopsida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="37" pageNumber="190" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="order">Magnoliales</taxonomicName>
, but the character combination seen in the fossils is unknown in any extant family of the order (
<bibRefCitation author="Friis, E. M. &amp; Crane, P. R. &amp; Pedersen, K. R." box="[890,1076,1291,1315]" pageId="37" pageNumber="190" pagination="93 - 127" refId="ref75830" refString="Friis, E. M., Crane, P. R., Pedersen, K. R. (2019 a): Extinct diversity among Early Cretaceous angiosperms: meso- fossil evidence of early Magnoliales from Portugal. - International Journal of Plant Sciences, 180: 93 - 127. https: // doi. org / 10.1086 / 701319" type="journal article" year="2019">Friis et al. 2019a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
